  "text": "Applications of our results include in particular proving secrecy properties for some group protocols that manipulate unbounded lists, with an unbounded number of participants. In this paper, we focus mainly on group protocols and illustrate our work on the Asokan-Ginzboorg protocol [CITATION_1] . We prove secrecy of the session key exchanged in this protocol by verifying with ProVerif its version with lists of length one and the size of the group equal to one. Another possible application is the treatment of XML protocols such as web services, XML documents being modeled using possibly nested lists.",
